23class PropertyKey {
24 public:
25 inline PropertyKey(Isolate* isolate, double index);
26 // {name} might be a string representation of an element index.
27 inline PropertyKey(Isolate* isolate, Handle<Name> name);
28 // {valid_key} is a Name or Number.
29 inline PropertyKey(Isolate* isolate, Handle<Object> valid_key);
30 // {key} could be anything.
31 PropertyKey(Isolate* isolate, Handle<Object> key, bool* success);
32
33 inline bool is_element() const;
34 Handle<Name> name() const { return name_; }
35 size_t index() const { return index_; }

37
38 private:
39 friend LookupIterator;
40
41 // Shortcut for constructing PropertyKey from an active LookupIterator.
42 inline PropertyKey(Isolate* isolate, Handle<Name> name, size_t index);
43
44 Handle<Name> name_;
45 size_t index_;
46};

48class V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE LookupIterator final {
49 public:
50 enum Configuration {
51 // Configuration bits.
52 kInterceptor = 1 << 0,
53 kPrototypeChain = 1 << 1,
54
55 // Convenience combinations of bits.
56 OWN_SKIP_INTERCEPTOR = 0,
57 OWN = kInterceptor,
58 PROTOTYPE_CHAIN_SKIP_INTERCEPTOR = kPrototypeChain,
59 PROTOTYPE_CHAIN = kPrototypeChain | kInterceptor,
60 DEFAULT = PROTOTYPE_CHAIN
61 };
62
63 enum State {
64 // The property was not found by the iterator (this is a terminal state,
65 // iteration should not continue after hitting a not-found state).
66 NOT_FOUND,
67 // Typed arrays have special handling for "canonical numeric index string"
68 // (https://tc39.es/ecma262/#sec-canonicalnumericindexstring), where not
69 // finding such an index (either because of OOB, or because it's not a valid
70 // integer index) immediately returns undefined, without walking the
71 // prototype (https://tc39.es/ecma262/#sec-typedarray-get).
72 TYPED_ARRAY_INDEX_NOT_FOUND,
73 // The next lookup requires an access check -- we can continue iteration on
74 // a successful check, otherwise we should abort.
75 ACCESS_CHECK,
76 // Interceptors are API-level hooks for optionally handling a lookup in
77 // embedder code -- if their handling returns false, then we should continue
78 // the iteration, though we should be conscious that an interceptor may have
79 // side effects despite returning false and might invalidate the lookup
80 // iterator state.
81 INTERCEPTOR,
82 // Proxies are user-space hooks for handling lookups in JS code.
83 // https://tc39.es/ecma262/#proxy-exotic-object
84 JSPROXY,
85 // Accessors are hooks for property getters/setters -- these can be
86 // user-space accessors (AccessorPair), or API accessors (AccessorInfo).
87 ACCESSOR,
88 // Data properties are stored as data fields on an object (either properties
89 // or elements).
90 DATA,
91 // WasmGC objects are opaque in JS, and appear to have no properties.
92 WASM_OBJECT,
93
94 // A LookupIterator in the transition state is in the middle of performing
95 // a data transition (that is, as part of a data property write, updating
96 // the receiver and its map to allow the write).
97 //
98 // This state is not expected to be observed while performing a lookup.
99 TRANSITION,
100
101 // Set state_ to BEFORE_PROPERTY to ensure that the next lookup will be a
102 // PROPERTY lookup.
103 BEFORE_PROPERTY = INTERCEPTOR
104 };
105

362// Similar to the LookupIterator, but for concurrent accesses from a background
363// thread.
364//
365// Note: This is a work in progress, intended to bundle code related to
366// concurrent lookups here. In its current state, the class is obviously not an
367// 'iterator'. Still, keeping the name for now, with the intent to clarify
368// names and implementation once we've gotten some experience with more
369// involved logic.
370// TODO(jgruber, v8:7790): Consider using a LookupIterator-style interface.
371// TODO(jgruber, v8:7790): Consider merging back into the LookupIterator once
372// functionality and constraints are better known.
373class ConcurrentLookupIterator final : public AllStatic {
374 public:
375 // Tri-state to distinguish between 'not-present' and 'who-knows' failures.
376 enum Result {
377 kPresent, // The value was found.
378 kNotPresent, // No value exists.
379 kGaveUp, // The operation can't be completed.
380 };
381
382 // Implements the own data property lookup for the specialized case of
383 // fixed_cow_array backing stores (these are only in use for array literal
384 // boilerplates). The contract is that the elements, elements kind, and array
385 // length passed to this function should all be read from the same JSArray
386 // instance; but due to concurrency it's possible that they may not be
387 // consistent among themselves (e.g. the elements kind may not match the
388 // given elements backing store). We are thus extra-careful to handle
389 // exceptional situations.
390 V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE static base::Optional<Tagged<Object>> TryGetOwnCowElement(
391 Isolate* isolate, Tagged<FixedArray> array_elements,
392 ElementsKind elements_kind, int array_length, size_t index);
393
394 // As above, the contract is that the elements and elements kind should be
395 // read from the same holder, but this function is implemented defensively to
396 // tolerate concurrency issues.
397 V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE static Result TryGetOwnConstantElement(
398 Tagged<Object>* result_out, Isolate* isolate, LocalIsolate* local_isolate,
399 Tagged<JSObject> holder, Tagged<FixedArrayBase> elements,
400 ElementsKind elements_kind, size_t index);
401
402 // Implements the own data property lookup for the specialized case of
403 // strings.
404 V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE static Result TryGetOwnChar(Tagged<String>* result_out,
405 Isolate* isolate,
406 LocalIsolate* local_isolate,
407 Tagged<String> string,
408 size_t index);
409
410 // This method reimplements the following sequence in a concurrent setting:
411 //
412 // LookupIterator it(holder, isolate, name, LookupIterator::OWN);
413 // it.TryLookupCachedProperty();
414 // if (it.state() == LookupIterator::DATA) it.GetPropertyCell();
415 V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE static base::Optional<Tagged<PropertyCell>>
416 TryGetPropertyCell(Isolate* isolate, LocalIsolate* local_isolate,
417 Handle<JSGlobalObject> holder, Handle<Name> name);
418};
